Unconditional multi-level analyses revealed that 4.40 per cent of the variance in self-esteem is between schools (τ0 /(τ0 +σ2
), with σ2
 = 38.417, τ0  = 1.766, p < 0.001). Separate unconditional analyses showed that for vocational students 5.46 per cent of the variance in self-esteem was between schools; for academic students this was 3.38 per cent. Overall, school type was not significantly associated with self-esteem (Table 3, main effect model 2a), but the relationship between track and self-esteem differed according to school type, as was evident from the significant positive cross-level interaction coefficient (Table 3, Model 2a: γ = 1.162, p = 0.018). This coefficient indicated that the difference in self-esteem is larger between academic and vocational students attending multilateral schools, than between academic and vocational students attending categorial schools (Figure 2
). When the effect of track equalled 1.157 in categorial schools, it equalled 2.319 ( = 1.157 + 1.162) in multilateral schools. Multilateral schools clearly sharpen the difference in self-esteem between vocational and academic students. The interaction between track position and school type remained significant when taking into account GPA (Table 3, Model 2b).
